    "q1_6": [
      {
        "disclosure_cycle": "2025 Disclosure Cycle",
        "cdp_requesting_org_number": 779465,
        "requesting_organization": "CDP",
        "disclosing_org_type": "City",
        "cdp_region": "India",
        "discloser_country_or_area": "India",
        "public_status": "Public",
        "question_number": "Q1.6",
        "question_text": "Report your jurisdiction's most significant examples of collaboration with government, business, and/or civil society on climate-related issues.",
        "row_order": 1,
        "row_name": "Row 1",
        "col1_Primary entity collaborated with": "Civil society: Climate initiatives/networks",
        "col2_Mechanisms used to collaborate": "Reporting to the national Measurement, Reporting and Verification (MRV) system|Convening industry groups|Requirement to develop emissions inventory|Capacity development|Climate action plan implementation|Reporting of climate and/or environmental data|Knowledge or data sharing|Collaborative initiative|Technical assistance|Multi-jurisdictional regional collaboratives",
        "col3_Areas collaboration focused on": "Waste|Adaptation|Building and Infrastructure|Inclusive climate action and/or equity|Public health|Finance|Emissions reduction|Ecosystem restoration|Transport (Mobility)|Resilience|Energy",
        "col4_Description of collaboration and any progress, if applicable": "BMC works collaboratively with NGOs and climate expert organisations and networks such as C40 Cities, WRI, Waatavaran and so on, on the implementation of Climate actions in the city. City has collaborated with WRI on greening measures in the city for heat resilience and also in developing climate resilient streets through nature-based solutions. Several measures on air quality improvement and mobility are also being worked with WRI. BMC has been associated with C40 Cities since 2020 and has successfully launched the Paris agreement-aligned CAP in 2022 with the support of WRI as a Knowledge Partner. The first round of consultations for CAP was held with experts from NGOs, research organizations, citizens' forums, international development agencies and municipal service providers such as BEST and private companies. Six consultations were held in the first round, one for each sector. In each consultation, 5-7 subject experts shared specific recommendations, which formed the basis of the initial approach, goals and actions for each sectoral priority. These consultations were widely attended by climate enthusiasts, subject experts, students and citizens, with an average participation of 80-100 people. These consultations highlighted the key priorities and impact groups for each sector, with a focus on ensuring inclusivity in the planning process and representation of the needs of vulnerable citizens. The second round of consultations was hosted with various departments within BMC, external agencies such as Brinhanmumbai Electric Supply & Transport (BEST), Mumbai Port Trust (MbPT), Mumbai Metropolitan Region Development Authority (MMRDA), Maharashtra Pollution Control Board (MPCB) and DISCOMS such as TATA Power and Adani Electricity Mumbai Ltd. In this round, the overarching goals and actions were discussed and the participants shared their feedback and recommendations on priority actions proposed in the MCAP. This process helped assess the relevance and feasibility of actions, the status of projects underway and the key barriers to timely implementation. The third round of consultations was held at the ward level for seven administrative zones across three divisions - City, Western Suburbs and Eastern Suburbs. During these consultations, Assistant Commissioners (ACs) and zonal DMCs of the divisions were familiarized with the MCAP and the proposed actions. The officials shared their perspectives with respect to the challenges and priorities at the grassroots and offered their support and commitment for the implementation of MCAP at the ward level. The ACs' recommendations for increased capacities to monitor progress, track projects and ensure timely collaboration is reflected in the form of the recently set up Environment and Climate Change Department. BMC also released its Climate Budget this year which was also a result of support from expert organisations and from different departments in the city.\\n\\nNetworks like C40 helps the Environment and Climate Change department to further the climate actions in the city and the ULB by providing exposure to climate accelerators and network which serves as a platform for peer-to-peer knowledge exchange and also leading amongst the cities across the world to set an example of climate leadership. C40 also provides technical assistance to the city and is actively engaged in initiatives relevant to heat resilience in building sector and structuring implementation support for decarbonisation efforts in public buildings.\\nThere are many other such support that the city receives through climate initiatives and networks.",
        "col5_Other entities collaborated with": "Vulnerable population groups|Construction|Regional government|Waste|Real Estate|NGO and associations|Residents/community groups|Academia"
      }
    ],
