        "row_name": "Row 1",
        "col1_Climate-related hazards^": "Urban flooding",
        "col2_Vulnerable population groups most exposed": "Other: Coastal Communities|Frontline workers|Outdoor workers|Low-income households",
        "col3_Sectors most exposed^": "Sewerage, waste management and remediation activities|Water supply|Manufacturing|Fishing",
        "col4_Describe the impacts on vulnerable populations and sectors": "Around 35% of Mumbai's population lives within 250 m of flood hotspots exposing them to the high flood risk. Most of the informal settlements are located along the low-lying areas. Therefore, communities living in these settlements are more exposed to the risks associated with flood hazards. With frequent spells of heavy rainfall, the city has been witnessing extensive waterlogging. These recurrent waterlogging events also limit the means to access business centers impacting the daily wage/ industrial jobs the most. Based on Directory of Establishments' 2015 data, 73% of Mumbai's small & large industrial and commercial establishments are located within 500m of flood hotspots, exasperating their risk level. And 69% of the employees who work at these establishments have experienced hindered access due to physical disconnect caused by waterlogging in the area.Based on a 2013 study that ranked major coastal cities on their associated flood risks, Mumbai was placed fifth in the world with annual losses to the economy mounting to USD 284 million. Most of these losses are uninsured and borne by individuals or small businesses leading to increased and differential vulnerability. Heavy rainfall and flooding affect the sewage and drainage systems making them overflow which endangers public health.Shifting ocean currents and warming waters are changing the distribution of fish stocks and altering the structure of marine ecosystems. This has impacted the livelihoods of coastal communities in Mumbai.Heavy rainfall and flooding affect the transport infrastructure in a city by impacting its safety, operation costs, travel time and service regularity. This further disrupts access to most essential and critical civic services. Based on the flood hotspot influence zone analysis, 33% of Mumbai's mass transit network - including its lifelines of the suburban rail network, Metro line and Monorail - are heavily impacted by inundation limiting physical access to transit stations. On 25th July 2005, the Mumbai airport, built on reclaimed land from the Mithi river, was inundated for three days and was non-operational for more than 30 hours. Heavy rainfall increases road travel time from roughly 8% to 140% in some road sections, making it challenging to provide emergency response and recovery initiatives.",
        "col5_Proportion of the population exposed to the hazard": "31-40%",
