    "q1_3": [
      {
        "disclosure_cycle": "2025 Disclosure Cycle",
        "cdp_requesting_org_number": 779465,
        "requesting_organization": "CDP",
        "disclosing_org_type": "City",
        "cdp_region": "India",
        "discloser_country_or_area": "India",
        "public_status": "Public",
        "question_number": "Q1.3",
        "question_text": "Provide information on your jurisdiction's oversight of climate-related risks and opportunities and how these issues have impacted your jurisdiction's planning.",
        "row_order": 1,
        "row_name": "Response",
        "col1_Select the processes that reflect your jurisdiction's oversight of climate-related issues": "Climate-related issues are considered by the government when undertaking budgeting and/or major capital expenditures",
        "col2_Provide further details on your jurisdiction's oversight of climate-related issues": "The Rajkot Net-zero Climate Resilient City Action Plan (Towards A Net-zero future by 2070) is developed based on an urban system gap analysis; climate risk and vulnerability assessment; baseline GHG emissions inventory; future emissions scenario modelling including BAU projections and GHG emissions reduction scenarios (Progressive Action Scenario and Net-zero Pathway). Rajkot has opted for the sectoral goals and targets of the Net-zero Pathway and outlined priority adaptation and mitigation strategies and actions to help improve the city's urban climate resilience. Spearheaded by the RMC and the climate core team, the development of Net-zero CRCAP involved input from various government departments, research institutions, non-governmental organizations (NGOs), and community representatives. This inclusive approach ensured that a wide range of perspectives were considered, leading to the development of a robust and comprehensive climate action plan. This plan will serve as a detailed roadmap, specifying the necessary institutional mechanisms, technical capabilities, and communication channels required to effectively integrate climate action into urban planning and infrastructure. Please refer below sections from the Rajkot's 'Climate Resilient City Action Plan (Towards A Net-zero future by 2070). 1) Annexure 1 Formation of Stakeholder Committee and Climate Core Team (Page 255 to 259); 2) Chapter 4 (section 4.1.6, 4.2.5,4.3.2, 4.4.8, 4.5.6, 4.6.2) for information on sector wise Budgetary planning for climate actions in FY 2023-24.",
        "col3_Describe how climate-related issues have impacted your jurisdiction's master/development planning": "The Second Revised Draft Development Plan, 2031 has been prepared in 2016 considering the demand of projected population for the next two decades for the entire area of 686 sq.km. under the Rajkot Urban Development Authority (RUDA), including the Rajkot city area. The implementation of the development plan is facilitated through town planning schemes that utilize the land pooling concept to enhance neighbourhood-level infrastructure. This approach involves land reconstitution, the development of road networks, and the establishment of social and physical infrastructure. RUDA has proposed a 2nd ring road around the city in 2016 which connects major highways and supports ease of traffic movement, particularly for industrial freights. To preserve the ecological balance and boost agriculture activities, the developable zone is restricted till 2nd ring road. Certain pockets between RMC and 2nd ring road are proposed as an agriculture zone. Also, along with agricultural activities, development of agro-based industries and processing units are allowed to support activities like farming, livestock etc. in conjunction with development regulations. The planned and authorized strategy aids in the local administration's ability to organize, think through, and carry out initiatives for each fiscal year by including them in the cities yearly implementation plan (municipal budget). Please refer section 3.6 of chapter 3 from Rajkot Climate Resilient City Action Plan (Towards A Net-zero future by 2070) for land use and development planning.",
        "col4_Describe how climate-related issues have impacted your jurisdiction's financial planning": "Based on Rajkot Climate Resilient City Action Plan (Towards A Net Zero Future by 2070) and climate related issues, city has proposed various climate resilient interventions, which has increased capital allocation of Annual Municipal Budget (i.e., lake interlinking, replacing old water supply and sewerage network, RE plants, developing urban forests to increase in green cover, biomining of legacy waste etc.). A list of projects to be implemented is included in the city's Climate Resilient City Action Plan (CRCAP). The CRCAP has been given council approval, making it simpler to get funds for its implementation. Every year, the city chooses a specific area to focus on, and projects relating to low-carbon growth in that area are included in the financial budget of the city so that they may be implemented and monitored. From last 3 years, city is focusing on Transport sector and has allocated funding for deploying EV in public transportation, promoting e-auto for first and last mile connectivity and promoting use of NMT. Considering that city has establish dedicated charging station for e-buses and has announced viability gap funding of INR 30000 for the purchase of e-auto. City also provided subsidy of INR 1000 for the purchase of cycle to its citizens.Please refer below sections from the Rajkot's 'Climate Resilient City Action Plan (Towards A Net-zero future by 2070). 1) Annexure 1 Formation of Stakeholder Committee and Climate Core Team (Page 255 to 259); 2) Chapter 4 (section 4.1.6, 4.2.5,4.3.2, 4.4.8, 4.5.6, 4.6.2) for information on sector wise Budgetary planning for climate actions in FY 2023-24.",
        "col5_Describe the risks to your jurisdiction related to the transition to a low-carbon economy": "Since low-carbon techniques demand substantial initial capital expenditures, public acceptance of them is poor. The government has begun to spark citizens' interest by proposing subsidies to give capital assistance.A mature technology improvement that facilitates a seamless transition to low carbon development is also required.City has not faced any risks in moving forward with this transition. Technical capacity of the city is limited for accessing climate finance, particularly for tapping international finance."
      }
    ],
