    "q2_1_1": [
      {
        "disclosure_cycle": "2025 Disclosure Cycle",
        "cdp_requesting_org_number": 779465,
        "requesting_organization": "CDP",
        "disclosing_org_type": "City",
        "cdp_region": "India",
        "discloser_country_or_area": "India",
        "public_status": "Public",
        "question_number": "Q2.1.1",
        "question_text": "Provide details on your climate risk and vulnerability assessment.",
        "row_order": 1,
        "row_name": "Row 1",
        "col1_Assessment attachment^": "CRVA_Rajkot_net_zero_CRCAP.pdf",
        "col2_Assessment direct link^": "https://drive.google.com/file/d/1nuCD4500zkFWIj04YcB7beq1IFIgJ7Vc/view?usp=drive_link",
        "col3_Confirm attachment/link provided to assessment": "The assessment has been attached and can be accessed (unrestricted) on the link provided",
        "col4_Boundary of assessment relative to jurisdiction boundary^": "Same - covers entire jurisdiction and nothing else",
        "col5_Year of publication or approval": 2024.0,
        "col6_Factors considered in assessment": "A process has been established to update the assessment at least every five years|Assessment includes consultation with partners|Assessment includes a high-emissions scenario (i.e., RCP 8.5)|Assessment considers transition risks|Assessment considers nature|Assessment includes sectors and/or urban systems|Assessment considers water security|A process has been established for prioritizing identified hazards|Identified hazards have been incorporated into the jurisdiction's overall risk management framework|Assessment considers vulnerable populations",
        "col7_Please explain": "According to the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC), risks of climate-related impacts result from the interaction of climate related hazards, vulnerability, and exposure of human and natural systems. Climate Risk and Vulnerability Assessment for Rajkot includes the analysis of risks and vulnerability of urban systems and population of Rajkot city due to climate hazards and air pollution. This baseline assessment supported city to adopt climate sensitive urban planning, effectively manage climate change induced risks, and efficiently implement climate resilient policies and interventions. The Climate Risk and Vulnerability Assessment (CRVA) follows ICLEI South Asia's 'Towards Net Zero ClimateResilientCITIES' methodology. Climate Risk and Vulnerability Assessment for Rajkot is divided into three parts that address; i) analysis of climate trends and projection scenario, ii) assessment and prioritization of hazards and risks based on likelihood and consequences, and iii) vulnerability assessment. Inputs from the climate core team and the stakeholder committee of RMC, captured through Shared Learning Dialogues (SLDs), are considered in the assessment. Step 1: Climate Trends and Projections Historic climate and weather data from 1972 to 2021 was analysed to understand trends and patterns of change in temperature and rainfall. Climate projections for Representative Concentration Pathways (RCPs) till 2070, were derived from the State Action Plan on Climate Change (SAPCC), Gujarat 2021. This information was substantiated with inputs from experts during stakeholder consultations. Based on the trend analysis and future projections, climate scenario statements were developed. Step 2: Risk Assessment Based on climate trends and projections, climate risks were identified and analysed according to the likelihood of occurrence and consequence. Inferences drawn from GIS based spatial analysis and analysis of relevant climate and qualitative information received during stakeholder consultations, informed the climate risk assessment. Information from the State Disaster Management Plan (Gujarat 2021) and Rajkot District Disaster Management Plan (2022) corroborated the results. It was observed that the city of Rajkot is vulnerable to extreme heat, urban floods, and air pollution. Vulnerable urban systems due to extreme heat, urban flood and air pollution were assessed. Step 3: Vulnerability Assessment Results from the risk assessment, along with data received from various departments of RMC, and qualitative information received during stakeholder consultations and one to one meetings, were used to assess the vulnerability of urban systems and their impact on people. The impacts on vulnerable groups such as low-income populations (focusing on hawkers, street side vendors, and slum dwellers), women, children, people with disabilities and the uneducated were also assessed. Vulnerable areas were identified following spatial analysis - Maps reflecting this analysis are included. The impacts of climate risks and air pollution on basic urban services (water, wastewater, stormwater, solid waste management, transport, urban greens) and emergency services (hospitals and fire services) were examined. Ward wise complaints, by urban sector and complaint types, from RMC's Comprehensive Complaints Redressal System (CCRS), were spatially analysed; this information supported the identification of areas that are vulnerable to fragile urban systems. For each urban system, the populations that are most vulnerable are also identified and their adaptive capacity is assessed in terms of their access to resources, access to information and their capacity to respond to stresses. Hotspot areas or highly vulnerable wards were identified through a map overlay technique, wherein geospatial information on complaints, climate risks/hazards and gaps in urban infrastructure and/or services were superimposed and analysed. Details and inferences of the climate vulnerability assessment are included in section 5.3 of attached Rajkot Climate Resilient City Action Plan . Please refer Chapter 5 from attached Rajkot Climate Resilient City Action Plan (Towards A Net Zero Future).ate risk and vulnerability assessment of fragile urban systems in Rajkot was undertaken while preparing its climate-resilient city action plan (CRCAP)"
      }
    ],
