    "q2_1_1": [
      {
        "disclosure_cycle": "2025 Disclosure Cycle",
        "cdp_requesting_org_number": 779465,
        "requesting_organization": "CDP",
        "disclosing_org_type": "City",
        "cdp_region": "India",
        "discloser_country_or_area": "India",
        "public_status": "Public",
        "question_number": "Q2.1.1",
        "question_text": "Provide details on your climate risk and vulnerability assessment.",
        "row_order": 1,
        "row_name": "Row 1",
        "col2_Assessment direct link^": "https://drive.google.com/file/d/1SC8ITuhFl41CndU8e2TYueebcxKJNxPY/view",
        "col3_Confirm attachment/link provided to assessment": "The assessment can be accessed (unrestricted) on the link provided",
        "col4_Boundary of assessment relative to jurisdiction boundary^": "Same - covers entire jurisdiction and nothing else",
        "col5_Year of publication or approval": 2025.0,
        "col6_Factors considered in assessment": "Assessment considers water security|Identified hazards have been incorporated into the jurisdiction's overall risk management framework|Assessment considers transition risks|Assessment considers vulnerable populations|Assessment considers nature|Assessment includes sectors and/or urban systems|Assessment includes consultation with partners|A process has been established to update the assessment at least every five years|A process has been established for prioritizing identified hazards|Assessment includes a high-emissions scenario (i.e., RCP 8.5)",
        "col7_Please explain": "According to the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change (IPCC), climate-related risks arise from the interaction of climate hazards, vulnerability, and exposure of both human and natural systems. The Climate Risk and Vulnerability Assessment (CRVA) for Vijayawada evaluates the risks and vulnerabilities faced by the city's urban systems and population due to climate hazards such as urban flooding, cyclones, landslides, heat stress, and air pollution. This baseline assessment has enabled the city to adopt climate-sensitive urban planning practices, enhance the management of climate-induced risks, and promote the effective implementation of climate-resilient policies and interventions.\\n\\nThe CRVA draws on ICLEI South Asia's 'Towards Net Zero ClimateResilientCITIES' methodology and is structured into three key components:\\n\\nAnalysis of Climate Trends and Projections:\\nHistoric climate and weather data from 1991 to 2021 were examined to identify trends and changes in temperature and rainfall. Future climate scenarios, based on Representative Concentration Pathways (RCPs) extending to 2079, were derived using hydrological and climate modeling by IIT Madras and supplemented with expert consultations. This analysis informed the development of climate scenario statements that guide planning.\\n\\nAssessment of Climate Hazards and Impacts:\\nPast occurrences of climate-induced hazards, their severity, and associated losses were analyzed to understand temporal patterns. GIS-based spatial analysis identified exposure hotspots within the city. These findings were validated using data from the city's Disaster Management Plan, research reports, and stakeholder consultations. Population groups exposed to these hazards were mapped, confirming that the city is vulnerable to urban floods, heat stress, cyclones, and landslides. Section 5.3 provides detailed insights from this hazard and hotspot assessment, including the spatial vulnerability of various urban systems.\\n\\nRisk and Vulnerability Assessment:\\nThe fragility and risk status of different urban systems were assessed in relation to the projected climate scenarios. This was based on both quantitative departmental data and qualitative inputs from stakeholder engagement. The assessment covered water supply, stormwater management, wastewater systems, solid waste management, transport, and public health, and utilized spatial analysis at the ward level. Hotspot areas were identified through overlays of geospatial data on service complaints, hazard exposure, and infrastructure gaps. These maps, presented in Section 5.5.2, further enabled the quantification of vulnerable communities, such as low-income groups.\\n\\nAdditionally, key actors for each urban system and the most at-risk population groups were identified. Their adaptive capacity was evaluated in terms of resource access, information availability, and ability to cope with climate stressors (see Section 5.5.4).\\n\\nInputs from the Climate Core Team and the Stakeholder Committee of Vijayawada Municipal Corporation, gathered through Shared Learning Dialogues (SLDs), were integral to the assessment process.\\n\\nComprehensive findings and analyses from the climate vulnerability assessment are available in Section 5 (pages 89-123) of the attached Vijayawada Net-zero Climate Resilient City Action Plan 2047."
      }
    ],
