        "col1_Climate-related hazards^": "Heat stress",
        "col2_Vulnerable population groups most exposed": "Women and girls|Low-income households|Children and youth|Outdoor workers|Vulnerable health groups|Elderly|Other: Pedestrians, Cyclists, People using two wheelers",
        "col3_Sectors most exposed^": "Construction|Human health and social work activities|Water supply|Transportation and storage|Electricity, gas, steam and air conditioning supply",
        "col4_Describe the impacts on vulnerable populations and sectors": "Vijayawada is experiencing a rising trend in both maximum and minimum surface air temperatures, with extreme heat events recorded in recent years. Heat-stress and impact analysis of satellite imagery shows that several city areas consistently exhibit land surface temperatures above the mean (33 degrees Celsius), indicating they are hotspots. This increase in heat conditions leads to thermal discomfort, reduced productivity, a rise in heat-related illnesses, and especially affects vulnerable groups like slum dwellers and outdoor workers. Overlay studies indicate that 75% of the city's slum population (i.e., 0.22 million people out of 0.29 million) is likely to be affected by high temperatures.\\n\\nHigher temperatures also impact urban services, including increasing water demand, challenging the capacity of water supply infrastructure, accelerating waste decomposition, compromising worker health and waste management systems, damaging road surfaces, and increasing energy demand for cooling. \\n\\nRefer to Section 5.3.1 in the attached Vijayawada Net-zero Climate Resilient City Action Plan ",
