        "col1_Climate-related hazards^": "Hurricanes, cyclones, and/or typhoons",
        "col2_Vulnerable population groups most exposed": "Elderly|Vulnerable health groups|Frontline workers|Low-income households|Outdoor workers|Children and youth|Women and girls",
        "col3_Sectors most exposed^": "Water supply|Waste management|Human health and social work activities|Sewerage, waste management and remediation activities|Transportation and storage|Construction|Electricity, gas, steam and air conditioning supply",
        "col4_Describe the impacts on vulnerable populations and sectors": "Vijayawada, located 70 km from the coast, is highly vulnerable to cyclones, having experienced 33 cyclonic disturbances within 150 km of the city between 1877 and 2013. Severe cyclonic events, such as those in 1977 and 1990, brought extremely high wind speeds and significant impacts to the city. UNDP study on Vijayawada city disaster management plan estimates that the entire city could experience severe cyclonic storms with wind speeds exceeding 89 km/h every 50 to 100 years, with the majority of wards at risk from storms reaching up to 151 km/h. Slum populations are especially at risk due to their often temporary housing structures.\\n\\nCyclones pose a serious threat to urban infrastructure, frequently overwhelming stormwater systems and causing waterlogging, supply disruptions, infrastructure damage, and increased exposure to flood and health risks.\\n\\nRefer to Section 5.3.4 in the attached Vijayawada Net-zero Climate Resilient City Action Plan. ",
