        "col16_Progress made towards target": "Vijayawada plans to implement a phased conversion of commercial fleets serving hospitals, schools, corporate companies, and government organizations to electric vehicles (EVs). The city will pilot low-emission zones in areas with heavy freight activity, such as vegetable and flower markets, where only electric commercial goods vehicles will be permitted. Efforts will focus on promoting the exclusive use of EV and CNG Light Duty Vehicles (LDVs) within city limits, and on incentivizing their adoption through measures such as parking fee waivers, one-time subsidies, dedicated parking facilities, special loading/unloading zones, and flexible entry times. New tenders for municipal and public services, such as waste, sanitation, health, and airport freight, will mandate a minimum EV share. To support this transition, EV charging stations will be established near major freight hubs and industrial clusters, and opportunities for collaboration under the e-FAST India platform will be explored. Dedicated truck terminals with parking and charging will be developed at the city's periphery, creating transfer hubs for efficient and sustainable freight movement.\\n\\nThe Vijayawada Net-zero Climate Resilient City Action Plan Annexure report provides 'Key Performance Indicators' against each action to monitor and evaluate the achievement of proposed targets (See Annexure L, pages 84 to 109). "
