        "discloser_country_or_area": "India",
        "public_status": "Public",
        "question_number": "Q9.1",
        "question_text": "Describe the outcomes of the most significant adaptation actions your jurisdiction is currently undertaking. Note that this can include those in the planning and/or implementation phase.",
        "row_order": 2,
        "row_name": "Row 2",
        "col1_Select a reference ID for the action": "Adaptation Action 2",
        "col2_Action^": "Engineered and built environment actions: Storm and wastewater management",
        "col3_Climate hazard(s) that action addresses": "Other: Health hazards",
        "col4_Action description and web link to further information^^": "Vijayawada city has made wastewater sector adaptation a key focus area by investing approximately INR 190 crores to expand its underground sewerage network and provide household service connections throughout previously uncovered regions. Currently, about 70% of the city is served by a piped centralized sewer system, while 30% rely on septic tanks and on-site sanitation solutions. The new initiative aims to extend seamless coverage to 100% of households by 2030, ensuring safe collection and conveyance of 194 MLD of projected wastewater.\\n\\nThe city is also rehabilitating old, dilapidated sewer networks to reduce leakage and blockages, deploying SCADA-enabled monitoring at sewage pumping stations and treatment plants, and strengthening maintenance for underground drainage to prevent overflows\u2014especially during heavy rainfall and floods. These systemic upgrades will significantly lower public health risks associated with open drains and overflow, improve resilience to climate-driven flooding, and enhance urban environmental quality.\\n\\nBeyond sewage collection coverage, Vijayawada city is also prioritizing the safe reuse of treated wastewater, particularly for industrial and urban non-potable applications. The focus is on increasing the reuse rate of treated water from 31% to 50% by 2030, with special plans for the Autonagar industrial area, which has high demand for non-potable water in cooling and cleaning processes. The city is upgrading existing and building new treatment plants\u2014incorporating energy-efficient, low-carbon anaerobic treatment technologies with methane gas capture\u2014to meet stringent standards and enable large-scale safe reuse. \\n\\nMeasures include mapping potential users, creating infrastructure for conveyance, launching awareness campaigns to encourage adoption across industries, and linking occupancy certificates for new developments to onsite reuse systems. These interventions not only strengthen climate resilience against water scarcity and pollution but also support circular urban resource flows and reduce dependency on freshwater, aligning with state and national sustainability goals.",
        "col5_Sectors adaptation action applies to": "Human health and social work activities|Sewerage, wastewater management and remediation activities|Water supply",
        "col6_Select the attributes of resilience this action enhances": "Planning & strategy|Infrastructural assets|Coordination & governance|Basic services|Technology assets|Anticipation & preparedness|Community participation|Decision-making capacity|Availability of diverse options",
        "col7_Co-benefits realized": "Economic: Job creation|Environmental: Reduced GHG emissions|Economic: Revenue generation|Public Health: Reduced disaster/disease/contamination-related health impacts",
